    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "7. The manager's suggestion to use $X = Y$ is a Naive Estimator.\n",
        "* If we use $X = Y$, our error variance would be $E[(X-Y)^2] = E[Q^2] = 4$.\n",
        "* By using $E[X|Y] = 0.2Y$, our error variance is only $0.8$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The factor $0.2$ is called a shrinkage estimator. It tells us that when a sensor is noisy, the \"best\" guess is to be conservative and pull the reading back toward the historical average (zero). If the power spikes, we don't immediately assume the tool is melting; we assume most of that spike is just the material being tough."
